          <td>8%&#8211;25%</td>
          <td>15%&#8211;60%</td>
          <td>25%&#8211;120%+ (with incentives)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Best For</strong></td>
          <td>Passive LPs, blue-chip pairs</td>
          <td>Semi-active LPs, mid-cap pairs</td>
          <td>Active LPs, yield maximizers</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>Raydium: The Blue-Chip Workhorse</h3>

  <p>Raydium remains Solana&#8217;s most liquid DEX, processing over $2 billion in weekly volume as of Q2 2026. Its <strong>constant product pools</strong> are ideal for long-term passive LPs who want exposure to blue-chip Solana pairs (SOL/USDC, SOL/USDT, SOL/mSOL) without active management. The trade-off is lower APRs (8&#8211;25%) compared to concentrated-liquidity alternatives.</p>

  <p>Raydium&#8217;s <strong>Fusion Pools</strong> (CPMM model) allow concentrated liquidity within a configurable weight curve, bridging the gap between standard and concentrated AMMs. Fusion Pools earn higher fees than standard pools but require slightly more attention.</p>

  <h3>Orca: The Concentrated Liquidity Pioneer</h3>

  <p>Orca introduced <strong>Whirlpools</strong> &#8212; Solana&#8217;s first concentrated liquidity AMM. LPs select a price range (e.g., $120&#8211;$180 for SOL/USDC) and earn fees only when trades occur within that band. Orca&#8217;s fee tiers range from 0.03% (stable pairs like USDC/USDT) to 1.0% (exotic pairs), giving LPs flexibility to match risk appetite with yield expectations.</p>

  <p>Orca also features <strong>double-dip yield</strong>: LPs earn both swap fees and ORCA token incentives through the protocol&#8217;s liquidity mining program. For active LPs who rebalance weekly, Orca Whirlpools can deliver 20&#8211;60% APR on blue-chip pairs.</p>

  <h3>Meteora: The Yield Maximization Engine</h3>

  <p>Meteora has emerged as the highest-yield DEX on Solana in 2026, thanks to its <strong>Dynamic Liquidity Market Maker (DLMM)</strong> and <strong>Dynamic Vaults</strong>. DLMM allows LPs to distribute capital across multiple price bins, each with its own fee tier, creating a granular liquidity curve that adapts to market conditions.</p>

  <p>Meteora&#8217;s key innovation for 2026 is <strong>single-sided staking</strong> through Dynamic Vaults &#8212; LPs can deposit just one token (e.g., SOL) while the vault algorithm manages the paired position. This eliminates the complexity of dual-token LP management while still earning swap fees and incentives. Yield on Meteora can range from 25% APR (conservative single-sided) to 120%+ (aggressive DLMM with incentive boosts).</p>

  <!-- SECTION 4: Impermanent Loss -->
  <h2>Impermanent Loss: What Every Solana LP Must Understand</h2>

  <p>Impermanent loss (IL) is the most misunderstood risk in DeFi liquidity provision. It occurs when the price ratio of your deposited tokens changes relative to the time you deposited them. The loss is &ldquo;impermanent&rdquo; only if you hold the position until the prices return to the original ratio &#8212; which may never happen.</p>

  <h3>Impermanent Loss Calculation Example</h3>

  <p>Let&#8217;s walk through a realistic example using a SOL/USDC pool:</p>

  <div class="glass-card">
    <p><strong>Scenario:</strong> You deposit $5,000 worth of tokens into a Raydium SOL/USDC pool when SOL is trading at $100.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>You deposit: <strong>25 SOL</strong> ($2,500) + <strong>2,500 USDC</strong> ($2,500) = $5,000 total</li>
      <li>The pool has a constant product: <em>25 &times; 2,500 = 62,500</em></li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>After 30 days, SOL price rises to $150</strong> (50% increase):</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Arbitrageurs trade in the pool until the price reflects $150/SOL</li>
      <li>New pool balance: ~20.41 SOL + ~3,061 USDC</li>
      <li>Your share is now worth: (20.41 &times; $150) + $3,061 = <strong>$6,122.50</strong></li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Vs. HODL strategy:</strong> If you had held 25 SOL ($3,750) + $2,500 USDC = <strong>$6,250</strong></p>
    <p><strong>Impermanent Loss:</strong> $6,250 &#8722; $6,122.50 = <strong>$127.50 (2.04%)</strong></p>
  </div>

  <p>In this example, you still made a profit ($1,122.50) because SOL appreciated &#8212; but you earned <strong>$127.50 less</strong> than if you simply held both tokens. In a bear market where one token drops 50%, IL amplifies the loss significantly.</p>

  <div class="table-wrapper">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Price Change</th>
          <th>Impermanent Loss</th>
          <th>Real IL Impact ($5k Deposit)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>&plusmn;10%</td>
          <td>~0.5%</td>
          <td>~$25</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>&plusmn;25%</td>
          <td>~2.0%</td>
          <td>~$100</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>&plusmn;50%</td>
          <td>~5.7%</td>
          <td>~$285</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>&plusmn;75%</td>
          <td>~11.1%</td>
          <td>~$555</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>&plusmn;100%</td>
          <td>~20.0%</td>
          <td>~$1,000</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="highlight-box">
    <p><strong>IL Mitigation Strategy:</strong> Pair assets that tend to move together (correlated pairs). SOL-staked SOL pairs (SOL/mSOL, SOL/jitoSOL) have minimal price divergence, resulting in IL below 0.5% even during volatile periods. Stable-stable pairs (USDC/USDT) have near-zero IL.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- SECTION 5: Yield Farming Strategies -->
  <h2>Yield Farming Strategies: Single-Sided vs LP Pairs</h2>

  <p>Not all yield farmers are the same. Your strategy depends on your capital, time commitment, and risk tolerance. Here&#8217;s how the two primary approaches compare.</p>

  <h3>Single-Sided Staking (Meteora Dynamic Vaults)</h3>

  <div class="success-box">
    <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Beginners, passive investors, concentrated capital deployment without dual-token complexity.</p>
  </div>

  <p>Meteora&#8217;s Dynamic Vaults allow you to stake a single asset (SOL, USDC, or JitoSOL) while the vault algorithm handles the paired position. The vault actively manages the LP range to maximize fees while minimizing IL exposure. Key metrics:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Typical APR:</strong> 15&#8211;45% (depending on the vault and incentive program)</li>
    <li><strong>Capital efficiency:</strong> 80&#8211;100% utilization of your deposit</li>
    <li><strong>Management:</strong> Zero active work &#8212; vault auto-adjusts position ranges</li>
    <li><strong>Risks:</strong> Vault smart contract risk, lower APRs than active DLMM positions</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>LP Pair Staking (Dual-Token Pools)</h3>

  <div class="success-box">
    <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Intermediate to advanced LPs, those with correlated pair strategies, yield maximizers willing to actively manage positions.</p>
  </div>

  <p>Providing liquidity in a dual-token pair on any of the three DEXs gives you direct exposure to swap fees and liquidity mining rewards. This is the classic LP strategy and offers the highest potential returns:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Typical APR (standard pools):</strong> 8&#8211;25% on Raydium, 15&#8211;40% on Orca Whirlpools</li>
    <li><strong>Typical APR (concentrated pools):</strong> 30&#8211;120%+ on Meteora DLMM with incentive programs</li>
    <li><strong>Capital efficiency:</strong> 100% (all capital allocated to earning fees)</li>
    <li><strong>Management:</strong> Weekly rebalancing recommended for concentrated positions</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="warning-box">
    <p><strong>Important:</strong> Dual-token LP positions in volatile pairs can suffer significant IL. Always model your IL exposure before committing capital. A good rule of thumb: if the pool APR is less than 3x the expected IL over your holding period, the risk-adjusted return may not be worth it.</p>
  </div>

